description: NaZnP is Matlockite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. Na(1)¹⁺ is bonded to five equivalent P(1)³⁻ atoms to form distorted NaP₅ trigonal bipyramids that share corners with twelve equivalent Zn(1)P₄ tetrahedra, corners with four equivalent Na(1)P₅ trigonal bipyramids, edges with four equivalent Zn(1)P₄ tetrahedra, and edges with eight equivalent Na(1)P₅ trigonal bipyramids. There is one shorter (2.955 Å) and four longer (3.035 Å) Na(1)-P(1) bond lengths. Zn(1)²⁺ is bonded to four equivalent P(1)³⁻ atoms to form ZnP₄ tetrahedra that share corners with four equivalent Zn(1)P₄ tetrahedra, corners with twelve equivalent Na(1)P₅ trigonal bipyramids, edges with four equivalent Zn(1)P₄ tetrahedra, and edges with four equivalent Na(1)P₅ trigonal bipyramids. All Zn(1)-P(1) bond lengths are 2.518 Å. P(1)³⁻ is bonded in a 9-coordinate geometry to five equivalent Na(1)¹⁺ and four equivalent Zn(1)²⁺ atoms.

Nb₃TeI₇ crystallizes in the trigonal P3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Nb₃TeI₇ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb(1)³⁺ is bonded to one Te(1)²⁻, one I(3)¹⁻, two equivalent I(1)¹⁻, and two equivalent I(2)¹⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing NbTeI₅ octahedra. The Nb(1)-Te(1) bond length is 2.735 Å. The Nb(1)-I(3) bond length is 3.072 Å. Both Nb(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 2.767 Å. Both Nb(1)-I(2) bond lengths are 2.937 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)³⁺ atoms. There are three inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)³⁺ atoms. In the third I¹⁻ site, I(3)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)³⁺ atoms.

UI₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two UI₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. U(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 8-coordinate geometry to two equivalent I(2)¹⁻ and six equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms. Both U(1)-I(2) bond lengths are 3.112 Å. There are four shorter (3.239 Å) and two longer (3.409 Å) U(1)-I(1) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent U(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent U(1)³⁺ atoms.

TiNCl crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TiNCl sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to four equivalent N(1)³⁻ and two equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing TiN₄Cl₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 23°. There are two shorter (2.006 Å) and two longer (2.016 Å) Ti(1)-N(1) bond lengths. Both Ti(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.458 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded in a see-saw-like geometry to four equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ atoms. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

Ca(SbO₂)₄ crystallizes in the monoclinic Cm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two Ca(SbO₂)₄ sheets oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. Ca(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 7-coordinate geometry to one O(2)²⁻, two equivalent O(5)²⁻, two equivalent O(6)²⁻, and two equivalent O(7)²⁻ atoms. The Ca(1)-O(2) bond length is 2.600 Å. Both Ca(1)-O(5) bond lengths are 2.473 Å. Both Ca(1)-O(6) bond lengths are 2.385 Å. Both Ca(1)-O(7) bond lengths are 2.427 Å. There are four inequivalent Sb+3.50+ sites. In the first Sb+3.50+ site, Sb(1)+3.50+ is bonded to one O(2)²⁻, two equivalent O(4)²⁻, and two equivalent O(5)²⁻ atoms to form SbO₅ square pyramids that share corners with two equivalent Sb(3)O₆ octahedra and edges with two equivalent Sb(1)O₅ square pyramids. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 49°. The Sb(1)-O(2) bond length is 2.128 Å. Both Sb(1)-O(4) bond lengths are 2.298 Å. Both Sb(1)-O(5) bond lengths are 2.168 Å. In the second Sb+3.50+ site, Sb(2)+3.50+ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one O(4)²⁻ and two equivalent O(3)²⁻ atoms. The Sb(2)-O(4) bond length is 2.000 Å. Both Sb(2)-O(3) bond lengths are 2.112 Å. In the third Sb+3.50+ site, Sb(3)+3.50+ is bonded to one O(1)²⁻, one O(6)²⁻, two equivalent O(2)²⁻, and two equivalent O(8)²⁻ atoms to form SbO₆ octahedra that share corners with two equivalent Sb(1)O₅ square pyramids, corners with two equivalent Sb(4)O₅ square pyramids, and edges with two equivalent Sb(3)O₆ octahedra. The Sb(3)-O(1) bond length is 1.981 Å. The Sb(3)-O(6) bond length is 1.964 Å. Both Sb(3)-O(2) bond lengths are 2.141 Å. Both Sb(3)-O(8) bond lengths are 2.038 Å. In the fourth Sb+3.50+ site, Sb(4)+3.50+ is bonded to one O(3)²⁻, two equivalent O(1)²⁻, and two equivalent O(7)²⁻ atoms to form distorted SbO₅ square pyramids that share corners with two equivalent Sb(3)O₆ octahedra and edges with two equivalent Sb(4)O₅ square pyramids. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 55°. The Sb(4)-O(3) bond length is 2.142 Å. Both Sb(4)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.224 Å. Both Sb(4)-O(7) bond lengths are 2.199 Å. There are eight inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal planar geometry to one Sb(3)+3.50+ and two equivalent Sb(4)+3.50+ atoms. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded to one Ca(1)²⁺, one Sb(1)+3.50+, and two equivalent Sb(3)+3.50+ atoms to form distorted corner-sharing OCaSb₃ trigonal pyramids. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal planar geometry to one Sb(4)+3.50+ and two equivalent Sb(2)+3.50+ atoms. In the fourth O²⁻ site, O(4)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Sb(2)+3.50+ and two equivalent Sb(1)+3.50+ atoms. In the fifth O²⁻ site, O(5)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted rectangular see-saw-like geometry to two equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and two equivalent Sb(1)+3.50+ atoms. In the sixth O²⁻ site, O(6)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to two equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and one Sb(3)+3.50+ atom. In the seventh O²⁻ site, O(7)²⁻ is bonded in a rectangular see-saw-like geometry to two equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and two equivalent Sb(4)+3.50+ atoms. In the eighth O²⁻ site, O(8)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent Sb(3)+3.50+ atoms.

PdPSe crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pbcn space group. There is one shorter (2.327 Å) and one longer (2.329 Å) Pd(1)-P(1) bond length. There are a spread of Pd(1)-Se(1) bond distances ranging from 2.494-3.393 Å. P(1) is bonded to two equivalent Pd(1)²⁺, one P(1), and one Se(1)²⁻ atom to form distorted PPPd₂Se tetrahedra that share corners with five equivalent Pd(1)P₂Se₃ square pyramids and corners with two equivalent P(1)PPd₂Se tetrahedra. The P(1)-P(1) bond length is 2.222 Å. The P(1)-Se(1) bond length is 2.317 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Pd(1)²⁺ and one P(1) atom.

CaCO₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. Ca(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 12-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(2)²⁻ and eight equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (2.506 Å) and two longer (2.775 Å) Ca(1)-O(2) bond lengths. There are a spread of Ca(1)-O(1) bond distances ranging from 2.449-2.949 Å. There are two inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to four equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and one C(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to four equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and one C(1)⁴⁺ atom.

As₂S₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two As₂S₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. There are two inequivalent As³⁺ sites. In the first As³⁺ site, As(1)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one S(1)²⁻, one S(2)²⁻, and one S(3)²⁻ atom. The As(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.308 Å. PdTe₂ is Calaverite structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PdTe₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. ZrTe₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ZrTe₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. TiCl₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two TiCl₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are two inequivalent Ti³⁺ sites. AlSiTe₃ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one AlSiTe₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. SbAsO₄ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one SbAsO₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb₃IrSe₈ is trigonal omega-derived structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic Cc space group. The Nb(3)-Se(3) bond length is 2.573 Å. The Nb(3)-Se(4) bond length is 2.672 Å. The Nb(3)-Se(5) bond length is 2.695 Å. The Nb(3)-Se(6) bond length is 2.562 Å. The Nb(3)-Se(7) bond length is 2.535 Å. Ir(1)³⁺ is bonded to one Se(1)²⁻, one Se(2)²⁻, one Se(5)²⁻, one Se(6)²⁻, one Se(7)²⁻, and one Se(8)²⁻ atom to form IrSe₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Nb(1)Se₆ octahedra, edges with two equivalent Nb(2)Se₆ octahedra, and edges with two equivalent Nb(3)Se₆ octahedra. The Ir(1)-Se(1) bond length is 2.574 Å. The Ir(1)-Se(2) bond length is 2.566 Å. The Ir(1)-Se(5) bond length is 2.565 Å. The Ir(1)-Se(6) bond length is 2.562 Å. The Ir(1)-Se(7) bond length is 2.562 Å. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)+4.33+, one Nb(2)+4.33+, and one Ir(1)³⁺ atom. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)+4.33+, one Nb(2)+4.33+, and one Ir(1)³⁺ atom. In the fourth Se²⁻ site, Se(4)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Nb(1)+4.33+, one Nb(2)+4.33+, and one Nb(3)+4.33+ atom. In the sixth Se²⁻ site, Se(6)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)+4.33+, one Nb(3)+4.33+, and one Ir(1)³⁺ atom. YbCl₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Immm space group. Yb(1)³⁺ is bonded in a body-centered cubic geometry to two equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ and six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. LuSBr crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one LuSBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. PbI₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PbI₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. SbBr₃ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pnma space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of four SbBr₃ clusters. PrTe₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two PrTe₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. Al₂Te₅ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Al₂Te₅ sheet oriented in the (2, 0, -1) direction. MnO₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one MnO₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. BiTeI crystallizes in the trigonal P3m1 space group. Nb₂CuS₄ is beta indium sulfide-derived structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Nb₂CuS₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb(1)+3.50+ is bonded to one S(1)²⁻ and three equivalent S(2)²⁻ atoms to form distorted NbS₄ trigonal pyramids that share corners with three equivalent Cu(1)S₆ octahedra and corners with six equivalent Nb(1)S₄ trigonal pyramids. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 58°. The Nb(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.290 Å. All Nb(1)-S(2) bond lengths are 2.415 Å. Cu(1)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form CuS₆ octahedra that share corners with six equivalent Nb(1)S₄ trigonal pyramids and edges with six equivalent Cu(1)S₆ octahedra. All Cu(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.455 Å. There are two inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded to one Nb(1)+3.50+ and three equivalent Cu(1)¹⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing SNbCu₃ trigonal pyramids. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)+3.50+ atoms.

MnSe is lead oxide structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one MnSe sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mn(1)²⁺ is bonded to four equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing MnSe₄ tetrahedra. All Mn(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.383 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Mn(1)²⁺ atoms.

Te₄O₉ crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Te₄O₉ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are two inequivalent Te+4.50+ sites. In the first Te+4.50+ site, Te(1)+4.50+ is bonded in a distorted rectangular see-saw-like geometry to one O(1)²⁻, one O(2)²⁻, and two equivalent O(3)²⁻ atoms. The Te(1)-O(1) bond length is 2.060 Å. The Te(1)-O(2) bond length is 1.946 Å. There is one shorter (1.934 Å) and one longer (2.153 Å) Te(1)-O(3) bond length. In the second Te+4.50+ site, Te(2)+4.50+ is bonded in an octahedral geometry to three equivalent O(1)²⁻ and three equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. All Te(2)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.937 Å. All Te(2)-O(2) bond lengths are 1.981 Å. There are three inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted bent 150 degrees geometry to one Te(1)+4.50+ and one Te(2)+4.50+ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted bent 120 degrees geometry to one Te(1)+4.50+ and one Te(2)+4.50+ atom. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a bent 120 degrees geometry to two equivalent Te(1)+4.50+ atoms.

CoCl₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three CoCl₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Co(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CoCl₆ octahedra. All Co(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.423 Å. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Co(1)²⁺ atoms.

Lix₀CoO₂ is Cyanogen Chloride-derived structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two Lix₀CoO₂ clusters. Co(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. Both Co(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.587 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Co(1)⁴⁺ atom.

Ba(BSe₃)₂ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmce space group. Ba(1)²⁺ is bonded to four equivalent Se(2)+1.33- and eight equivalent Se(1)+1.33- atoms to form BaSe₁₂ cuboctahedra that share corners with four equivalent Ba(1)Se₁₂ cuboctahedra, corners with four equivalent B(1)Se₄ tetrahedra, edges with four equivalent Ba(1)Se₁₂ cuboctahedra, and edges with six equivalent B(1)Se₄ tetrahedra. There are two shorter (3.411 Å) and two longer (3.787 Å) Ba(1)-Se(2) bond lengths. There are four shorter (3.546 Å) and four longer (3.744 Å) Ba(1)-Se(1) bond lengths. B(1)³⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Se(1)+1.33- and two equivalent Se(2)+1.33- atoms to form BSe₄ tetrahedra that share corners with two equivalent Ba(1)Se₁₂ cuboctahedra, edges with three equivalent Ba(1)Se₁₂ cuboctahedra, and  an edgeedge with one B(1)Se₄ tetrahedra. Both B(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.041 Å. Both B(1)-Se(2) bond lengths are 2.091 Å. There are two inequivalent Se+1.33- sites. In the first Se+1.33- site, Se(2)+1.33- is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Ba(1)²⁺ and two equivalent B(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second Se+1.33- site, Se(1)+1.33- is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to two equivalent Ba(1)²⁺ and one B(1)³⁺ atom.

Mg(ReO₄)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Mg(ReO₄)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mg(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form MgO₆ octahedra that share corners with six equivalent Re(1)O₄ tetrahedra. All Mg(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.062 Å. Re(1)⁷⁺ is bonded to one O(2)²⁻ and three equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form ReO₄ tetrahedra that share corners with three equivalent Mg(1)O₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 16°. The Re(1)-O(2) bond length is 1.740 Å. All Re(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.755 Å. There are two inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to one Mg(1)²⁺ and one Re(1)⁷⁺ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Re(1)⁷⁺ atom.

NpOI is Matlockite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one NpOI sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Np(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and four equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Np(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.318 Å. All Np(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.372 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Np(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing ONp₄ tetrahedra. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Np(1)³⁺ atoms.

ZnWO₄ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two ZnWO₄ sheets oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. W(1)⁶⁺ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to two equivalent O(1)²⁻ and four equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. Both W(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.798 Å. There are two shorter (1.918 Å) and two longer (2.213 Å) W(1)-O(2) bond lengths. Zn(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to two equivalent O(1)²⁻ and two equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. Both Zn(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.963 Å. Both Zn(1)-O(2) bond lengths are 2.017 Å. There are two inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent W(1)⁶⁺ and one Zn(1)²⁺ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a bent 120 degrees geometry to one W(1)⁶⁺ and one Zn(1)²⁺ atom.

YOI crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three YOI sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Y(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and three equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms. There is one shorter (2.265 Å) and three longer (2.326 Å) Y(1)-O(1) bond lengths. All Y(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.137 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Y(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing OY₄ tetrahedra. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Y(1)³⁺ atoms.

HgCl₂ is High Pressure (4-7GPa) Tellurium structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pnma space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of four HgCl₂ clusters. Hg(1)²⁺ is bonded in a distorted linear geometry to one Cl(1)¹⁻ and one Cl(2)¹⁻ atom. The Hg(1)-Cl(1) bond length is 2.327 Å. The Hg(1)-Cl(2) bond length is 2.328 Å. There are two inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Hg(1)²⁺ atom. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Hg(1)²⁺ atom.

Sc₂NCl₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Sc₂NCl₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sc(1)+2.50+ is bonded to three equivalent N(1)³⁻ and three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing ScN₃Cl₃ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Sc(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 2.273 Å. All Sc(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.566 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Sc(1)+2.50+ atoms to form edge-sharing NSc₆ octahedra. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Sc(1)+2.50+ atoms.

ErAg(PSe₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two ErAg(PSe₃)₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Er(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form ErSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ag(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Er(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.845 Å. Ag(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form AgSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Er(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Ag(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.932 Å. P(1)+3.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. All P(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.219 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Er(1)³⁺, one Ag(1)²⁺, and one P(1)+3.50+ atom.

WS₂ is Molybdenite structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two WS₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. W(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing WS₆ pentagonal pyramids. All W(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.425 Å. S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent W(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

PdTeI₂ crystallizes in the triclinic P̅1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PdTeI₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pd(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ and three equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing PdTe₃I₃ octahedra. There are a spread of Pd(1)-Te(1) bond distances ranging from 2.640-2.754 Å. There are a spread of Pd(1)-I(1) bond distances ranging from 2.805-2.873 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded to three equivalent Pd(1)⁴⁺ and two equivalent I(2)¹⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing TePd₃I₂ square pyramids. There is one shorter (3.170 Å) and one longer (3.186 Å) Te(1)-I(2) bond length. There are two inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Pd(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms.

Pt₂TlTe₃ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. There are two inequivalent Pt+2.50+ sites. In the first Pt+2.50+ site, Pt(1)+2.50+ is bonded to six equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing PtTe₆ octahedra. All Pt(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.723 Å. In the second Pt+2.50+ site, Pt(2)+2.50+ is bonded to two equivalent Tl(1)¹⁺ and four equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms to form PtTl₂Te₄ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Pt(1)Te₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Pt(2)Tl₂Te₄ octahedra. Both Pt(2)-Tl(1) bond lengths are 2.962 Å. All Pt(2)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.677 Å. Tl(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Pt(2)+2.50+ and three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms. All Tl(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 3.513 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to one Pt(1)+2.50+, two equivalent Pt(2)+2.50+, and one Tl(1)¹⁺ atom.

PbF₄ crystallizes in the tetragonal I4/mmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two PbF₄ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pb(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent F(1)¹⁻ and four equivalent F(2)¹⁻ atoms to form corner-sharing PbF₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. Both Pb(1)-F(1) bond lengths are 2.004 Å. All Pb(1)-F(2) bond lengths are 2.170 Å. There are two inequivalent F¹⁻ sites. In the first F¹⁻ site, F(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Pb(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the second F¹⁻ site, F(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Pb(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

AlP crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/mbm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one AlP sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Al(1)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent P(1)³⁻ atoms. There is one shorter (2.250 Å) and two longer (2.292 Å) Al(1)-P(1) bond lengths. P(1)³⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Al(1)³⁺ atoms.

NbTlOBr₄ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two NbTlOBr₄ sheets oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. Nb(1)⁵⁺ is bonded to two equivalent O(1)²⁻, two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻, and two equivalent Br(2)¹⁻ atoms to form distorted corner-sharing NbBr₄O₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. There is one shorter (1.815 Å) and one longer (2.200 Å) Nb(1)-O(1) bond length. Both Nb(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.583 Å. Both Nb(1)-Br(2) bond lengths are 2.571 Å. Tl(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a body-centered cubic geometry to four equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ and four equivalent Br(2)¹⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (3.393 Å) and two longer (3.436 Å) Tl(1)-Br(1) bond lengths. There are two shorter (3.342 Å) and two longer (3.386 Å) Tl(1)-Br(2) bond lengths. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁵⁺ atoms. There are two inequivalent Br¹⁻ sites. In the first Br¹⁻ site, Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 1-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)⁵⁺ and two equivalent Tl(1)¹⁺ atoms. In the second Br¹⁻ site, Br(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a 1-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)⁵⁺ and two equivalent Tl(1)¹⁺ atoms.

LiVF₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. Li(1)¹⁺ is bonded to two equivalent F(1)¹⁻ and two equivalent F(2)¹⁻ atoms to form corner-sharing LiF₄ tetrahedra. Both Li(1)-F(1) bond lengths are 1.894 Å. Both Li(1)-F(2) bond lengths are 1.845 Å. V(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 7-coordinate geometry to one F(2)¹⁻ and six equivalent F(1)¹⁻ atoms. The V(1)-F(2) bond length is 2.025 Å. There are four shorter (2.111 Å) and two longer (2.531 Å) V(1)-F(1) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent F¹⁻ sites. In the first F¹⁻ site, F(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to one Li(1)¹⁺ and three equivalent V(1)²⁺ atoms. In the second F¹⁻ site, F(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to two equivalent Li(1)¹⁺ and one V(1)²⁺ atom.

MoS₂ is Molybdenite structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two MoS₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mo(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing MoS₆ pentagonal pyramids. All Mo(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.419 Å. S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Mo(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

BN is Boron Nitride-like structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two BN sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. B(1)³⁺ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms. All B(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 1.450 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent B(1)³⁺ atoms.

Si₃H crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Si₃H sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are three inequivalent Si sites. In the first Si site, Si(1) is bonded to one Si(2) and three equivalent Si(1) atoms to form corner-sharing SiSi₄ tetrahedra. The Si(1)-Si(2) bond length is 2.392 Å. All Si(1)-Si(1) bond lengths are 2.380 Å. In the second Si site, Si(2) is bonded to one Si(1) and three equivalent Si(3) atoms to form corner-sharing SiSi₄ tetrahedra. All Si(2)-Si(3) bond lengths are 2.368 Å. In the third Si site, Si(3) is bonded in a single-bond geometry to three equivalent Si(2) and one H(1) atom. The Si(3)-H(1) bond length is 1.507 Å. H(1) is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Si(3) atom.

SnSe is Halite, Rock Salt structured and crystallizes in the cubic Fm̅3m space group. Sn(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing SnSe₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Sn(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 3.030 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Sn(1)²⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing SeSn₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted.

CrSe is Vulcanite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CrSe sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Cr(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. All Cr(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.431 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Cr(1)²⁺ atoms.

ErSeI crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ErSeI sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Er(1)³⁺ is bonded to four equivalent Se(1)²⁻ and two equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing ErSe₄I₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 12°. There are two shorter (2.813 Å) and two longer (2.842 Å) Er(1)-Se(1) bond lengths. Both Er(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.006 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a rectangular see-saw-like geometry to four equivalent Er(1)³⁺ atoms. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Er(1)³⁺ atoms.

Mg(SnN)₂ crystallizes in the tetragonal P̅4m2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Mg(SnN)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mg(1)²⁺ is bonded to four equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms to form corner-sharing MgN₄ tetrahedra. All Mg(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 2.081 Å. Sn(1)²⁺ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms. Both Sn(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 2.117 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to two equivalent Mg(1)²⁺ and two equivalent Sn(1)²⁺ atoms to form corner-sharing NMg₂Sn₂ tetrahedra.

AsCl₅ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two AsCl₅ clusters. As(1)⁵⁺ is bonded in a trigonal bipyramidal geometry to one Cl(3)¹⁻, two equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻, and two equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms. The As(1)-Cl(3) bond length is 2.177 Å. Both As(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.269 Å. Both As(1)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 2.185 Å. There are three inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(3)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one As(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one As(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the third Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one As(1)⁵⁺ atom.

CoI₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CoI₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Co(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CoI₆ octahedra. All Co(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 2.736 Å. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Co(1)²⁺ atoms.

C₃N crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two C₃N sheets oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. There are two inequivalent C¹⁺ sites. In the first C¹⁺ site, C(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent C(2)¹⁺ atoms. Both C(1)-C(2) bond lengths are 1.309 Å. In the second C¹⁺ site, C(2)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one C(1)¹⁺ and two equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms. Both C(2)-N(1) bond lengths are 1.583 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to four equivalent C(2)¹⁺ atoms.

CrF₂ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/c space group. Cr(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent F(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing CrF₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles range from 49-56°. There are a spread of Cr(1)-F(1) bond distances ranging from 1.987-2.466 Å. F(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent Cr(1)²⁺ atoms.

SnO₂ crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three SnO₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sn(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing SnO₆ octahedra. All Sn(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.123 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Sn(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

MoTe₂ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two MoTe₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mo(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ and three equivalent Te(2)²⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing MoTe₆ octahedra. There are two shorter (2.829 Å) and one longer (2.851 Å) Mo(1)-Te(1) bond length. There are two shorter (2.722 Å) and one longer (2.725 Å) Mo(1)-Te(2) bond length. There are two inequivalent Te²⁻ sites. In the first Te²⁻ site, Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Mo(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the second Te²⁻ site, Te(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Mo(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

GaTe is black P-derived structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of four GaTe sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ga(1)²⁺ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms. All Ga(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.701 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Ga(1)²⁺ atoms.

Li₂UI₆ is trigonal omega-derived structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two Li₂UI₆ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Li(1,2)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form LiI₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Li(1,2)I₆ octahedra and edges with three equivalent U(1)I₆ octahedra. All Li(1,2)-I(1) bond lengths are 2.997 Å. U(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form UI₆ octahedra that share edges with six equivalent Li(1,2)I₆ octahedra. All U(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.015 Å. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to two equivalent Li(1,2)¹⁺ and one U(1)⁴⁺ atom.

CdBr₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of six CdBr₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. MgBr₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one MgBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. BaH₂O₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmc2₁ space group. Ba(1) is bonded in a 8-coordinate geometry to two equivalent O(1), two equivalent O(2), and four equivalent O(3) atoms. WS₂ is Molybdenite-like structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two WS₂ sheets oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. TiNBr crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TiNBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. ScOBr crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ScOBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ga crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. Ga(1) is bonded to eight equivalent Ga(1) atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge, corner, and face-sharing GaGa₈ hexagonal bipyramids. There are a spread of Ga(1)-Ga(1) bond distances ranging from 2.752-2.907 Å.

PbTiO₃ crystallizes in the tetragonal P4mm space group. Ti(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a 5-coordinate geometry to one O(2)²⁻ and four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. The Ti(1)-O(2) bond length is 1.780 Å. HgPSe₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two HgPSe₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. LiFeF₄ is Anatase-derived structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal I4₁/a space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of four LiFeF₄ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb₃Cl₈ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two Nb₃Cl₈ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti₂O is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Ti₂O sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. MnBr₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one MnBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. TlF is TlF-II structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pbcm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TlF sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. CrP₂S₇ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CrP₂S₇ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. B₂(CN₂)₃ crystallizes in the trigonal R32 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three B₂(CN₂)₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. BiI₃ is Bismuth triodide-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one BiI₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Zr₂PTe₂ is MAX Phase-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Zr₂PTe₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pr₂Br₅ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. There are two inequivalent Pr sites. CrS₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CrS₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. AlSeBr₇ crystallizes in the monoclinic Pc space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of two AlSeBr₇ ribbons oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. AgHgSBr crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmma space group. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to two equivalent S(1)²⁻, one Br(1)¹⁻, and one Br(2)¹⁻ atom. BCl₃ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/m space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two BCl₃ clusters. B(1)³⁺ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. All B(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 1.743 Å. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one B(1)³⁺ atom.

Mg(OH)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Mg(OH)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mg(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing MgO₆ octahedra. All Mg(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.105 Å. H(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one O(1)²⁻ atom. The H(1)-O(1) bond length is 0.974 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to three equivalent Mg(1)²⁺ and one H(1)¹⁺ atom.

Nb₂S₂C is MAX Phase-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Nb₂S₂C sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to three equivalent C(1)⁴⁻ and three equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing NbC₃S₃ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Nb(1)-C(1) bond lengths are 2.256 Å. All Nb(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.515 Å. C(1)⁴⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms to form edge-sharing CNb₆ octahedra. S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

AgNO₂ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Imm2 space group. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 7-coordinate geometry to one N(1)³⁺ and six equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. The Ag(1)-N(1) bond length is 2.220 Å. There are two shorter (2.429 Å) and four longer (2.774 Å) Ag(1)-O(1) bond lengths. N(1)³⁺ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to one Ag(1)¹⁺ and two equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. Both N(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.266 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to three equivalent Ag(1)¹⁺ and one N(1)³⁺ atom.

HgF crystallizes in the tetragonal I4/mmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two HgF sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Hg(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 5-coordinate geometry to five equivalent F(1)¹⁻ atoms. There is one shorter (2.182 Å) and four longer (2.739 Å) Hg(1)-F(1) bond lengths. F(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 5-coordinate geometry to five equivalent Hg(1)¹⁺ atoms.

ThNCl is Matlockite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. Th(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a 9-coordinate geometry to four equivalent N(1)³⁻ and five equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Th(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 2.358 Å. There is one shorter (3.157 Å) and four longer (3.261 Å) Th(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Th(1)⁴⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing NTh₄ tetrahedra. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 5-coordinate geometry to five equivalent Th(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

Pt₂TlS₃ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. There are two inequivalent Pt+2.50+ sites. In the first Pt+2.50+ site, Pt(1)+2.50+ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing PtS₆ octahedra. All Pt(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.420 Å. In the second Pt+2.50+ site, Pt(2)+2.50+ is bonded to two equivalent Tl(1)¹⁺ and four equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form PtTl₂S₄ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Pt(1)S₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Pt(2)Tl₂S₄ octahedra. Both Pt(2)-Tl(1) bond lengths are 3.049 Å. All Pt(2)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.373 Å. Tl(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Pt(2)+2.50+ and three equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms. All Tl(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 3.242 Å. S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to one Pt(1)+2.50+, two equivalent Pt(2)+2.50+, and one Tl(1)¹⁺ atom.

Re(AgCl₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Re(AgCl₃)₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Re(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in an octahedral geometry to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Re(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.380 Å. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted trigonal planar geometry to three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Ag(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.556 Å. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted water-like geometry to one Re(1)⁴⁺ and one Ag(1)¹⁺ atom.

PbO is lead oxide structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PbO sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pb(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. All Pb(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.348 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Pb(1)²⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing OPb₄ tetrahedra.

RhCl₃ is Aluminum trichloride structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one RhCl₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Rh(1)³⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ and four equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing RhCl₆ octahedra. Both Rh(1)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 2.362 Å. There are two shorter (2.359 Å) and two longer (2.360 Å) Rh(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Rh(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Rh(1)³⁺ atoms.

AgGa(PSe₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two AgGa(PSe₃)₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ag(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form AgSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ga(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Ag(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.876 Å. Ga(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form GaSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ag(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Ga(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.659 Å. P(1)+3.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. All P(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.229 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Ag(1)²⁺, one Ga(1)³⁺, and one P(1)+3.50+ atom.

Ti₂PTe₂ is MAX Phase-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Ti₂PTe₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)+3.50+ is bonded to three equivalent P(1)³⁻ and three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing TiTe₃P₃ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Ti(1)-P(1) bond lengths are 2.495 Å. All Ti(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.788 Å. P(1)³⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Ti(1)+3.50+ atoms to form edge-sharing PTi₆ octahedra. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Ti(1)+3.50+ atoms.

AuTe₂Cl crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. Au(1)⁵⁺ is bonded to four equivalent Te(1)²⁻ and one Cl(1)¹⁻ atom to form distorted edge-sharing AuTe₄Cl square pyramids. All Au(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.720 Å. The Au(1)-Cl(1) bond length is 3.117 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Au(1)⁵⁺, one Te(1)²⁻, and three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. The Te(1)-Te(1) bond length is 2.825 Å. There is one shorter (3.268 Å) and two longer (3.390 Å) Te(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 7-coordinate geometry to one Au(1)⁵⁺ and six equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms.

FeCo₃O₈ is trigonal omega-derived structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three FeCo₃O₈ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Fe(1) is bonded to six equivalent O(1) atoms to form FeO₆ octahedra that share edges with six equivalent Co(1)O₆ octahedra. All Fe(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.865 Å. Co(1) is bonded to two equivalent O(2) and four equivalent O(1) atoms to form CoO₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Fe(1)O₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Co(1)O₆ octahedra. Both Co(1)-O(2) bond lengths are 1.875 Å. All Co(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.879 Å. There are two inequivalent O sites. In the first O site, O(1) is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Fe(1) and two equivalent Co(1) atoms. In the second O site, O(2) is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Co(1) atoms.

Cr₃O₈ crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃mc space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two Cr₃O₈ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Cr(1)+5.33+ is bonded to one O(3)²⁻, one O(4)²⁻, two equivalent O(1)²⁻, and two equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CrO₆ octahedra. The Cr(1)-O(3) bond length is 1.934 Å. The Cr(1)-O(4) bond length is 1.931 Å. Both Cr(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.819 Å. Both Cr(1)-O(2) bond lengths are 1.820 Å. There are four inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent Cr(1)+5.33+ atoms. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent Cr(1)+5.33+ atoms. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Cr(1)+5.33+ atoms. In the fourth O²⁻ site, O(4)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Cr(1)+5.33+ atoms.

TiBr₃ is Bismuth triodide structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three TiBr₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing TiBr₆ octahedra. There are three shorter (2.574 Å) and three longer (2.576 Å) Ti(1)-Br(1) bond lengths. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)³⁺ atoms.

TmAg(PSe₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two TmAg(PSe₃)₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Tm(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form TmSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ag(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Tm(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.833 Å. Ag(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form AgSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Tm(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Ag(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.931 Å. P(1)+3.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. All P(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.219 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Tm(1)³⁺, one Ag(1)²⁺, and one P(1)+3.50+ atom.

Bi₂Pt is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Bi₂Pt sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pt(1)²⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Bi(1)¹⁺ atoms to form edge-sharing PtBi₆ octahedra. All Pt(1)-Bi(1) bond lengths are 2.806 Å. Bi(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Pt(1)²⁻ atoms.

VBr₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one VBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. V(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing VBr₆ octahedra. All V(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.639 Å. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent V(1)²⁺ atoms.

Bi₂Se₃ is MAX Phase-derived structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three Bi₂Se₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ and three equivalent Se(2)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing BiSe₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Bi(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 3.106 Å. All Bi(1)-Se(2) bond lengths are 2.888 Å. There are two inequivalent Se²⁻ sites. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1)²⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms to form edge-sharing SeBi₆ octahedra. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms.

P₄Se₅ is alpha U structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pna2₁ space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of four P₄Se₅ clusters. There are four inequivalent P+2.50+ sites. In the first P+2.50+ site, P(1)+2.50+ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Se(2)²⁻ atom. The P(1)-Se(2) bond length is 2.255 Å. In the second P+2.50+ site, P(2)+2.50+ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ and one Se(5)²⁻ atom. The P(2)-Se(1) bond length is 2.311 Å. The P(2)-Se(5) bond length is 2.354 Å. In the third P+2.50+ site, P(3)+2.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Se(1)²⁻, one Se(2)²⁻, and one Se(4)²⁻ atom. The P(3)-Se(1) bond length is 2.308 Å. The P(3)-Se(2) bond length is 2.335 Å. The P(3)-Se(4) bond length is 2.315 Å. In the fourth P+2.50+ site, P(4)+2.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Se(3)²⁻, one Se(4)²⁻, and one Se(5)²⁻ atom. The P(4)-Se(3) bond length is 2.157 Å. The P(4)-Se(4) bond length is 2.301 Å. The P(4)-Se(5) bond length is 2.306 Å. There are five inequivalent Se²⁻ sites. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(2)+2.50+ and one P(3)+2.50+ atom. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(1)+2.50+ and one P(3)+2.50+ atom. In the third Se²⁻ site, Se(3)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one P(4)+2.50+ atom. In the fourth Se²⁻ site, Se(4)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(3)+2.50+ and one P(4)+2.50+ atom. In the fifth Se²⁻ site, Se(5)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one P(2)+2.50+ and one P(4)+2.50+ atom.

Nb₂O₅ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. Nb(1)⁵⁺ is bonded to one O(2)²⁻, two equivalent O(1)²⁻, and three equivalent O(3)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing NbO₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles range from 0-33°. The Nb(1)-O(2) bond length is 1.931 Å. There is one shorter (1.815 Å) and one longer (2.215 Å) Nb(1)-O(1) bond length. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁵⁺ atoms. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁵⁺ atoms. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)⁵⁺ atoms.

TaOI₂ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of two TaOI₂ sheets oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. Ta(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a distorted linear geometry to two equivalent O(1)²⁻, two equivalent I(1)¹⁻, and two equivalent I(2)¹⁻ atoms. Both Ta(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.949 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Ta(1)⁴⁺ atoms. There are two inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted water-like geometry to two equivalent Ta(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Ta(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

TiOBr crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TiOBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)³⁺ is bonded to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing TiBr₂O₄ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 6°. There are two shorter (2.024 Å) and two longer (2.066 Å) Ti(1)-O(1) bond lengths. Both Ti(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.586 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a see-saw-like geometry to four equivalent Ti(1)³⁺ atoms. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)³⁺ atoms.

PuOBr is Matlockite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PuOBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pu(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and four equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Pu(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.315 Å. All Pu(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 3.197 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Pu(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing OPu₄ tetrahedra. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Pu(1)³⁺ atoms.

AlN is Wurtzite structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6₃/mmc space group. Al(1)³⁺ is bonded to five equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing AlN₅ trigonal bipyramids. There are three shorter (1.913 Å) and two longer (2.094 Å) Al(1)-N(1) bond lengths. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to five equivalent Al(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing NAl₅ trigonal bipyramids.

CoBr₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CoBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Co(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CoBr₆ octahedra. All Co(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.571 Å. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Co(1)²⁺ atoms.

Lix₀CoO₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of six Lix₀CoO₂ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Co(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent O(1,2)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CoO₆ octahedra. All Co(1)-O(1,2) bond lengths are 1.877 Å. O(1,2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Co(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

Bi₂TiO₅ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. Ti(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent O(1)²⁻, two equivalent O(2)²⁻, and two equivalent O(3)²⁻ atoms to form distorted corner-sharing TiO₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 29°. Both Ti(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.849 Å. Both Ti(1)-O(2) bond lengths are 2.201 Å. Both Ti(1)-O(3) bond lengths are 2.075 Å. Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to one O(3)²⁻, two equivalent O(1)²⁻, and three equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. The Bi(1)-O(3) bond length is 2.623 Å. There is one shorter (2.243 Å) and one longer (2.552 Å) Bi(1)-O(1) bond length. There are two shorter (2.258 Å) and one longer (2.348 Å) Bi(1)-O(2) bond length. There are three inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Ti(1)⁴⁺ and two equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded to one Ti(1)⁴⁺ and three equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing OTiBi₃ tetrahedra. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted bent 150 degrees geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ and two equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms.

AuTe₂ is Calaverite structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one AuTe₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Au(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Te(1)+1.50- atoms to form edge-sharing AuTe₆ octahedra. There are two shorter (2.828 Å) and four longer (2.883 Å) Au(1)-Te(1) bond lengths. Te(1)+1.50- is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Au(1)³⁺ atoms.

HgPS₃ crystallizes in the triclinic P̅1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one HgPS₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Hg(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to one S(2)²⁻, one S(3)²⁻, and two equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms. The Hg(1)-S(2) bond length is 2.595 Å. The Hg(1)-S(3) bond length is 2.508 Å. There is one shorter (2.683 Å) and one longer (2.850 Å) Hg(1)-S(1) bond length. P(1)⁵⁺ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one S(1)²⁻, one S(2)²⁻, and one S(3)²⁻ atom. The P(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.055 Å. The P(1)-S(2) bond length is 2.029 Å. The P(1)-S(3) bond length is 2.051 Å. There are three inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Hg(1)¹⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted water-like geometry to one Hg(1)¹⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the third S²⁻ site, S(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted water-like geometry to one Hg(1)¹⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom.

Pd₃(PS₄)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Pd₃(PS₄)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pd(1)²⁺ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to four equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms. All Pd(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.364 Å. P(1)⁵⁺ is bonded in a distorted tetrahedral geometry to one S(2)²⁻ and three equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms. The P(1)-S(2) bond length is 1.919 Å. All P(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.140 Å. There are two inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Pd(1)²⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one P(1)⁵⁺ atom.

Sr₂MnSO₃ crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. There are two inequivalent Sr²⁺ sites. In the first Sr²⁺ site, Sr(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 9-coordinate geometry to five equivalent S(1)²⁻ and four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. There are four shorter (2.862 Å) and one longer (3.125 Å) Sr(1)-S(1) bond length. All Sr(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.687 Å. In the second Sr²⁺ site, Sr(2)²⁺ is bonded in a 9-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and five equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. All Sr(2)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.627 Å. There is one shorter (2.481 Å) and four longer (2.804 Å) Sr(2)-O(2) bond lengths. Mn(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to one S(1)²⁻, one O(2)²⁻, and four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form distorted corner-sharing MnSO₅ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 3°. The Mn(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.492 Å. The Mn(1)-O(2) bond length is 1.891 Å. All Mn(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.977 Å. Rb(SbSe₂)₂ crystallizes in the triclinic P̅1 space group. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 5-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Rb(1)¹⁺, one Sb(1)+3.50+, and one Sb(2)+3.50+ atom. In the third Se²⁻ site, Se(3)²⁻ is bonded in a 1-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Rb(1)¹⁺ and one Sb(2)+3.50+ atom. HgBr₂ is trigonal omega structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one HgBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. GeTe is Halite, Rock Salt structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R3m space group. Ge(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing GeTe₆ octahedra. ZrTe₅ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Cmcm space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of four ZrTe₅ ribbons oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. YOI crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one YOI sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. CeOBr is Matlockite structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CeOBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. FeCl₃ is Aluminum trichloride-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P312 space group. CdSbS₂Cl crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pnma space group. Sb(1)³⁺ is bonded to two equivalent S(1)²⁻ and three equivalent S(2)²⁻ atoms to form distorted SbS₅ square pyramids that share corners with four equivalent Cd(1)S₄Cl₂ octahedra, edges with three equivalent Cd(1)S₄Cl₂ octahedra, and edges with four equivalent Sb(1)S₅ square pyramids. Tl₂O is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of six Tl₂O sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. GaGeTe crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three GaGeTe sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ba(SnO₂)₄ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Ba(SnO₂)₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mg₅(HO₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Mg₅(HO₃)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. FePSe₃ crystallizes in the trigonal R̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of three FePSe₃ sheets oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. SrH₂O₃ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmc2₁ space group. ZrNI crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmn space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ZrNI sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. YCBr crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one YCBr sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. SbPO₄ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one SbPO₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction.
